<br>
First off, what is guild chat for?  The primary uses that I envision for it are:<br>
<br>
1. Getting groups together (duu)<br>
2. Short greetings to the guild like &quot;Hello all!&quot; &quot;Later hombres,&quot; or &quot;DING!! Hot diggity am I ever a stud!&quot;<br>
3. Making announcements to the guild, welcoming new members, giving away magic items,  ect.  <br>
4. Asking the guild for info or advice.<br>
5. Coordinating separate groups during multi-group raids.<br>
6. The rare case that you are in a group with two other guildies and you want to say something just to them (and not to the 4th member of your group).  If this situation comes up in a group that has only two guildies, it's better to use tell. <br>
<br>
The main thing that the guild chat is not for is stuff that is better handled with group chat or tells.  If it's only of interest to your group (ex. &quot;Hail goblin war chief&quot; or &quot;what  is our loot order&quot;) use group chat.  If it's only of interest to one other person use a tell.  Note that I myself (and many others in our guild apparently <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->     ) have a bad habit of typing &quot;/gu&quot; when we mean to type &quot;/g&quot; and vise versa.  This is no big deal at all.  I'm not talking about the occasional slip up, I'm talking about spamming the guild chat with 20 minutes of group specific dialogue.<br>
<br>
Besides these general guidelines, there are a few specific don'ts that I would like to suggest.  <br>
<br>
1. Avoid statements that imply racism, sexism, or any sort of bigotry.  <br>
<br>
For example statements such as &quot;Man I hate this sword, it's so gay looking&quot; or &quot;You fight like a woman&quot; might be offensive to some players since they imply that if you are gay or a woman you are automatically a &quot;wussy&quot; or inferior.  Now I fully realize that most players are going to understand that statments like the ones above are not meant in a derogatory way, and that you are only joking.  On the other hand  statements like &quot;Man I would I ever like to [insert verb] that dark elf&quot; or &quot;did you see the [instert body part] on that elf chick&quot; I think are really really inappropriate for guild chat.  Where the line between these two extremes is, I really can't say.  This is something we may want to think about for the final version of the guild chat guidlines.<br>
<br>
2. Avoid statements that are &quot;sketchy&quot; over guild chat.  <br>
<br>
By this I mean references to human waste, bodily fluids, &quot;used prophylactics&quot;, ect.  If in doubt. find a more delicate way to phrase things.  <br>
<br>
3. Statements that are abusive or insulting towards other guildies.  <br>
<br>
For example, if you think someone is &quot;a loot hog&quot; or is &quot;the greatest fool that ever lived and is getting the group killed&quot;, send them a tell with friendly advice.  Don't embarrass him or her by broadcasting your opinion over guild chat.  If you have consistent problems with a particular guildy and they refuse to heed your advice, bring it up with one of the guildmasters and w'll investigate (we don't want idgits in our guild after all).  But don't start a flame war over guild chat. <br>
<br>
4. If you vent over guild chat, spell any expletives properly so that the in-game profanity filter will catch them.  <br>
<br>
For example, work arounds like &quot;F.UK  I died again!&quot; are not appropriate.  Any one that still has their profanity filter up doesn't want to see profanity, and shouldn't have to. <br>
<br>
<br>
Well, that's all I can think of off the top of my head.  Keep in mind that we are a pretty laid back bunch, and only some-one that consistently and repeatedly violates these policies is going to be censured or booted (it has already happed to a few I'm sorry to say).  <br>
<br>
A few others have recently left because they found these rules stifling.  Personally, I prefer hearing nothing over guild chat in preference to comments about someone's genitalia, or their dog's genitalia, or the genitalia of characters that walk by,  or comments that imply that some-one lacks genitalia . . . but maybe I've been too anal.<br>
